displacement (\(p\)=0.0084), weight (\(p\)<0.001), year (\(p\)<0.001) and origin (\(p\)<0.001) have statistically significant relationship to the response.

The coefficient for the year variable suggests that every one unit increase in year is associated with an increase of mpg by an amount of 0.75.

rms::vif(lrm1)

Embarked is an problematic variable, so it would not be included in models.

Next, considering the limited use of non-linear terms for predictors that look important in a spearman \(\rho~^2~\) plot

plot(spearman2(Survived~ Pclass+Sex+Age+SibSp+Parch+Fare, data=train))

There might be an interaction term between sex and Pclass.

Discussion

By looking at the top one of the discussion in Kernels, what I’ve learn from them is their various ways of data visualization including Mosaic Plot and a fancy Alluvial Diagram. They also used various approach of modeling and predicting, which is good way of doing research other than using a single method. The aspect that I may did better than them is using C statistic and AIC as a model selection criteria whereas they focus only on the prediction accuracy rate of test data.

Chapter 4

logistic <- lrm(crim_bnr ~ zn + nox + age + dis + rad + tax + ptratio + 
    black + medv, data = Boston)

prob <- predict(logistic, type="fitted")
pred <- prediction(prob, Boston$crim_bnr)
perf <- performance(pred, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
auc <- performance(pred, measure="auc")


auc <- round(auc@y.values[[1]],3)
#aucB<-auc
roc.data <- data.frame(fpr=unlist(perf@x.values),
                       tpr=unlist(perf@y.values),
                       model="GLM")
ggplot(roc.data, aes(x=fpr, ymin=0, ymax=tpr)) +
    geom_ribbon(alpha=0.2) +
    geom_line(aes(y=tpr)) +
    ggtitle(paste0("ROC Curve for Model 1 w/ AUC=", auc))

This logistic regression model crim_bnr ~ zn + nox + age + dis + rad + tax + ptratio + black + medv has surprisingly good capabiliby of discriminating the crim classes with C statistic of 0.971.

KNN

library(class)
set.seed(471)

test.id<-sample(x = 1:506, size = 101, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL)

Boston$id<-1:506

test  <- Boston%>%filter(id %in% test.id)
train <- Boston[-which(Boston$id %in% test.id),]

knn1 <- knn(train = train[,c(-1,-15,-16)], 
            test = test[,c(-1,-15,-16)],
            cl = train$crim_bnr,
            k=1)

table(knn1, test$crim_bnr)
##     
## knn1  0  1
##    0 44  4
##    1  9 44
mean(knn1==test$crim_bnr)
## [1] 0.8712871
knn2 <- knn(train = train[,c(-1,-15,-16)], 
            test = test[,c(-1,-15,-16)],
            cl = train$crim_bnr,
            k=3)

mean(knn2==test$crim_bnr)
## [1] 0.9009901
knn3 <- knn(train = train[,c(-1,-15,-16)], 
            test = test[,c(-1,-15,-16)],
            cl = train$crim_bnr,
            k=5)

mean(knn3==test$crim_bnr)
## [1] 0.9207921
knn4 <- knn(train = train[,c(-1,-15,-16)], 
            test = test[,c(-1,-15,-16)],
            cl = train$crim_bnr,
            k=7)

mean(knn4==test$crim_bnr)
## [1] 0.9108911

It appears that when K=5 it has the largest prediction accuracy of 92%. This implies that the KNN approach dominates the logistic regression and LDA for this dataset.
